d hashing the CA bundle, a constants file to define the annotation key, and modifications to the deployments module to integrate the hash stamping and update the change detection logic. I'm reconsidering the idempotency mechanism here. The `createOrApplyDeployments` function uses `UpdateWithRetry` rather than strategic merge patch, so the guard relies on `hasObjectChanged` detecting whether the deployment has actually changed. When the CA bundle hash stays the same, the annotation won't change, so `hasObjectChanged` will return false and skip the update entirely. But the task seems to want something more explicit than that implicit guard. I need to add pod template annotation comparison to `deploymentSpecModified` since `hasObjectChanged` only checks top-level labels. I'm also reconsidering how to read the CNO-injected CA ConfigMap—the task requires reading the ConfigMap contents, which should be the trusted CA bundle in the operator namespace, similar to what the trustmanager does. Let me check if the istiocsr controller already has this capability.\n\nThe key insight is that the IstioCSR deployment needs to restart whenever the CNO-injected CA bundle changes. The implementation should read the ConfigMap, compute a SHA-256 hash of the PEM data, and stamp it as an annotation on the pod template to trigger the rolling restart.\n\nI'll create a new `configmaps.go` file in the istiocsr controller package, mirroring the pattern from trustmanager but tailored for this simpler use case where we just need to hash the CA bundle without creating additional ConfigMaps.\n\nWriting the ConfigMap handler... Completing the function to retrieve the CA bundle from the ConfigMap, handling the case where it's missing or empty, then defining a helper function that computes the SHA-256 hash of the bundle content and returns it as a hex string. the bundle data, and I need to decide whether a missing ConfigMap should be treated as an error or just return an empty hash. Since the CNO-injected CA bundle might not exist yet, I think the right approach is to return an empty hash without an error if the ConfigMap is missing or empty, but compute and stamp the hash when the data is present. Now I'm looking at the trustmanager pattern to understand what the idempotency guard should actually protect — it seems like it's meant to skip the deployment update when the hash hasn't changed, not just skip a ConfigMap patch. Writing the ConfigMap handler... Writing Go utility functions... I need to read the CA bundle and compute its hash before passing it to the deployment creation function, then handle the case where the bundle might be empty by computing a hash only if content exists.\n\nNow I'm updating the deployment signatures to accept the CA bundle hash as a parameter, and modifying the deployment object generation to use it.\n\nIn the utils file, I need to enhance the deployment comparison logic to also check pod template annotations, not just labels and container counts. I'm considering using `maps.Equal` for the annotation comparison to properly detect when the CA bundle hash annotation changes. Since `maps` is already imported in utils.go, I can use `maps.Equal` for the comparison. It handles nil and empty maps the same way, which is actually better semantics here than `reflect.DeepEqual`. Now I need to check whether the istiocsr controller actually watches the CNO-injected CA bundle ConfigMap—if it doesn't, changes to that ConfigMap won't trigger a reconciliation.\n\nLooking at the controller setup, it watches ConfigMaps but only those matching specific label predicates: either the managed resource label or the istiocsr resource watch label. The CNO-injected ConfigMap in the operator namespace likely doesn't have either label, so it won't currently trigger reconciliation when updated. That said, the task doesn't require me to add that functionality. The 30-second requeue interval should be sufficient for picking up changes to the CNO bundle ConfigMap, 